Data Cleaning

##changing the columns having discrete factors as categorical variables
g$termreason_desc=as.factor(g$termreason_desc)
g$termtype_desc=as.factor(g$termtype_desc)
g$BUSINESS_UNIT=as.factor(g$BUSINESS_UNIT)
g$gender_full=as.factor(g$gender_full)
g$gender_short=as.factor(g$gender_short)


## extracting unique last record value for each emp_id
g1=g %>% group_by(EmployeeID) %>% slice(n())

Feature Engineering

## converting the column variables having the dates to a date variable
g1$recorddate_key <- as.Date(g1$recorddate_key ,format='%m/%d/%Y')
g1$birthdate_key <- as.Date(g1$birthdate_key ,format='%m/%d/%Y')
g1$orighiredate_key <- as.Date(g1$orighiredate_key ,format='%m/%d/%Y')
g1$terminationdate_key<- as.Date(g1$terminationdate_key ,format='%m/%d/%Y')

## feature engineering to introduce new column for age
g1$age=as.integer(floor((g1$recorddate_key-g1$birthdate_key)/365)+2)
## feature engineering to introduce new column for length of service
g1$length_of_service=as.integer(ceiling((g1$recorddate_key-g1$orighiredate_key)/365))

###feature engineering to introduce new column to show active or terminated from the organisation
g1$status=ifelse(substring(g1$terminationdate_key,1,4)==1900,"Active","Terminated")
g1$status<-as.factor(g1$status)

Data Visualization

Preparing the dataset for visualization

## Data Visualization
theme_update(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) ## To have all plot titles at the centre
knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.width=15, fig.height=8) 

### extracting data for vancouver head office
v1=subset(g1,g1$city_name=="Vancouver" & g1$BUSINESS_UNIT=="HEADOFFICE")

## extracting data for all the stores
v2=subset(g1,g1$BUSINESS_UNIT=="STORES")

Data Visualization I: Office Location

#1. plotting business unit and city name to visualize the locations of the headoffice and the stores
ggplot(g1,aes(city_name,BUSINESS_UNIT))+geom_point(color="red",size=3) +coord_flip()+
  labs(y = "Business Unit", x = "City Name",title = "Location")

##conclusion- head office is located at vancouver

II Head Office: Employee Positions

#2. plotting job titles versus various departments for the head office
ggplot(v1,aes(department_name,job_title))+geom_point(size=3,color="orange")+
  labs(x="Department Name", y="Job Position", title = "Job Titles at the Head Office")

##inferences- from the plot we can classify the various jobs pertaining to a particular departments at the head office
## we also visualise the various hierarchy present for each job title within every department

III Stores: Employee Positions

#3. plotting job tittles versus various departments for the stores.
ggplot(v2,aes(department_name,job_title))+geom_point(size=3,color="orange")+
  labs(x="Department Name", y="Job Position", title = "Job Titles at the Stores")

##inferences- from the plot we can classify the various jobs pertaining to a particular departments at the stores

IV: Stores Locations

#4. number of stores in each city
ggplot(v2,aes(city_name,store_name))+geom_point(size=3,color="blue")+  coord_flip()+
  labs(y="Store Name", x="City Name", title = "Number of Stores in each City")

V Stores: Employees Distribution within British Columbia

#5. visulaising trend for number of people in each city wrt the job title in stores
ggplot(v2,aes(city_name,job_title))+geom_bin2d()+coord_flip()+
  labs(y="Job Title", x="City Name", title = "Number of Employees in each City")

VI: Gender Ratio

#6. Visualising the gender ratio at the head office and for the stores. 
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
pie(table(v1$gender_full),col=c("purple","yellow"),main = "Gender Ratio at the Head Office")
pie(table(v2$gender_full),col=c("blue","red"),main = "Gender Ratio at the Stores")

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

VII Stores: Gender Ratio

#7. Visualizing the gender ratio for the all the stores now independently.
ggplot(v2,aes(city_name))+geom_bar(aes(fill=gender_full))+coord_flip()+facet_grid(~BUSINESS_UNIT)+
  labs(y="Employee Count", x="City Name", title = "Gender Ratio for all the Stores")

VIII Head Office: Employee Distribution with the Years

#8. length of service versus age for head office gender-wise distribution
ggplot(v1,aes(age,length_of_service)) + geom_point(aes(color=factor(gender_full))) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(54,68), breaks = seq(min(v1$age),max(v1$age)+1,by=2)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(17,27), breaks = seq(min(v1$length_of_service),max(v1$length_of_service),by=2))+
  facet_wrap(~status)+
  labs(x="Age", y="Length of Service", title = "Employee Visualization at the Head Office")

IX Stores: Employee Distribution with the years

#9. length of service versus age for the stores gender wise distribution
ggplot(v2,aes(age,length_of_service)) + geom_point(aes(color=factor(gender_full))) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(20,67), breaks = seq(min(v2$age),max(v2$age)+1,by=2)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,27), breaks = seq(min(v2$length_of_service),max(v2$length_of_service),by=2))+
  facet_grid(status~.)+
  labs(x="Age", y="Length of Service", title = "Employee Visualization at the Stores")

X Employee Attrition

#10. attrition rate distribution with respect to gender
ggplot(g1,aes(status))+geom_bar(aes(fill=gender_full),position=position_dodge()) +
  facet_wrap(~BUSINESS_UNIT,scales = "free")+
  labs(x="Employment Status", y="Employee Count", title = "Overall Employee Attrition Rate Distribution")

#conclusion - number of people in store is more than the number of people in head office as expected
#conclusion-the ratio of male to female is almost the same in all the scenario

XI Employee Attrition with Age

#11. attrition rate distribution wrt age
ggplot(g1,aes(status,age))+geom_point(aes(color=factor(gender_full))) +
  facet_wrap(~BUSINESS_UNIT,scales = "free")+
  labs(x="Employment Status", y="Employee Age", title = "Employee Attrition Rate Distribution with respect to Age")

##conclusion- in head office people with age greater than 58 have left the organisation, and no such pattern is obserrved in stores

XII Employee Attrition Reason

#12. pie chart for overall termination reason 
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
lbls<-c("Layoff","Active","Resignation","Retirement")
pie3D(table(v1$termreason_desc),explode = 0.2,labels = lbls,radius = 0.7,theta=1,main = "Head Office Termination Reason")
pie3D(table(v2$termreason_desc),explode = 0.2,labels = lbls,radius = 0.7,theta=1,main = "Stores Termination Reason")

##conclusion- the majority people leaving the organisation is due to retirement 
par(mfrow=c(1,1))

XIII Employee Attrition Distribution within the Province

#13. City wise status of employees
ggplot(v2,aes(city_name))+geom_bar(aes(fill=status))+coord_flip()+
  labs(y="Employment Count", x="City Name", title = "Overall Employee Attrition Rate Distribution for each City")
